    "body": "## Problem\r\n\r\n`v:starttime` and by extension `:uptime` use a monotonic high-resolution timer. This only works as long as the timer keeps running (e.g. if the computer is suspended the timer is paused). This is somewhat unintuitive, as it doesn't match the behavior of the `uptime` shell command. \r\n\r\n## Solution\r\n\r\nI've opted to implement `os_realtime` to get the real time since the epoch in nanoseconds. On error, it returns 0, but from going over the implementations of `uv_clock_gettime` this should never error, as errors either come from wrong arguments or posix's `clock_gettime`, which in turn shouldn't error for getting the time with correct arguments and on the built-in real-time clock. Alternatively, `uv_clock_gettime` could be wrapped more faithfully like `uv_hrtime` is, but since it isn't used anywhere else right now this just shifts the error handling code to `main.c` where `v:starttime` is set.\r\n\r\nIf there are reasons to keep using a monotonic hr timer for `v:starttime` and `:uptime` this PR can be closed.\r\n\r\nMatrix discussion: https://matrix.to/#/!cylwlNXSwagQmZSkzs:matrix.org/$CtnEc3OCJa6ev8QzyqQGf0b4pyfMyxfNRDwCNE3mpQQ?via=matrix.org&via=gitter.im&via=libera.chat",
    "closed_at": "2026-04-27T23:01:48Z",
